.TH GSYNCH 1 "April 2026" "gsynch" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
gsynch \- deterministic one-way synchronization from a remote Git repository

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B gsynch
[\fIoptions\fR]

.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBgsynch\fR synchronizes the contents of a remote Git repository and branch
into the current working directory using Git's tree-restore mechanisms. It is
designed for deterministic, reproducible workflows where the remote repository
acts as the authoritative source of truth.

The tool performs a one-way mirror of the upstream tree into the local working
directory. Local changes are protected by default and require explicit override
flags to be overwritten.

If the current directory is empty, \fBgsynch\fR performs a clone of the
configured branch into \fB.\fR and removes the \fIorigin\fR remote to prevent
accidental pushes.

If the directory is not a Git repository, \fBgsynch\fR initializes one and
creates an initial commit from the existing contents to provide a baseline for
diffs and restores.

.SH OPTIONS

.TP
.BR --branch " " \fIBRANCH\fR
Branch name to synchronize from. Default: \fImain\fR.

.TP
.BR --url " " \fIURL\fR
Remote URL of the upstream repository. Required unless provided via
\fBGSYNCH_URL\fR.

.TP
.BR --only " " \fIPATH\fR
Restrict synchronization to a subdirectory of the upstream tree. Only files
under the specified path will be restored.

.TP
.BR --dry-run
Show what would happen without modifying the working tree or index. No files
are restored and no commits are created.

.TP
.BR --no-commit
Apply changes and stage them, but do not create a commit.

.TP
.BR --debug
Enable verbose debugging output, including local and remote commit graphs and
merge-base diagnostics.

.SS Override Options
\fBgsynch\fR classifies local state into three classes: staged, modified, and
untracked. By default, any local changes in these classes cause synchronization
to abort.

The following options allow selective overriding of this protection:

.TP
.BR --override-staged
Allow overwriting staged changes.

.TP
.BR --override-modified
Allow overwriting modified tracked files.

.TP
.BR --override-untracked
Allow overwriting untracked files whose paths collide with files in the
upstream tree.

.TP
.BR --override-all
Equivalent to enabling all override flags.

.SS Deletion Handling

.TP
.BR --no-local-delete
Preserve local files even if they were deleted in the upstream repository.
Upstream deletions are detected via diff-filter=D and skipped when this flag is
set.

.SS Forced Push Handling

.TP
.BR --allow-forced-push
Allow synchronization to continue even if a forced push is detected on the
upstream branch. By default, \fBgsynch\fR aborts when a forced push is detected.

.SS Help

.TP
.BR -h ", " --help
Show a brief help message and exit.

.SH BEHAVIOR

.SS Empty Directory
If the current directory contains no files, \fBgsynch\fR performs:

.nf
git clone --branch BRANCH URL .
git remote remove origin
.fi

and exits.

.SS Non-Git Directory
If the directory is not a Git repository, \fBgsynch\fR runs:

.nf
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial import of existing working directory"
.fi

to create a baseline commit.

.SS Local Change Classification
\fBgsynch\fR classifies local state into:

.IP 

\[bu]
\fIStaged\fR: tracked files with changes in the index.

.IP 

\[bu]
\fIModified\fR: tracked files with changes in the working tree.

.IP 

\[bu]
\fIUntracked\fR: files not tracked by Git.

.SS Default Blocking Behavior
Without override flags:

.IP 

\[bu]
Any staged or modified files cause \fBgsynch\fR to abort.

.IP 

\[bu]
Untracked files that would be overwritten cause \fBgsynch\fR to abort.

.SS Override Semantics
If any override flag is provided:

.IP 

\[bu]
Classes with an override are overwritten.

.IP 

\[bu]
Classes without an override are preserved.

.SS Upstream Deletion Behavior
Upstream deletions are detected via:

.nf
git diff --name-status --diff-filter=D HEAD..REMOTE
.fi

By default, deleted files are removed locally. With \fB--no-local-delete\fR,
these deletions are skipped.

.SS Subdirectory Synchronization
Use:

.nf
gsynch --only path/to/subdir
.fi

to restrict synchronization to a subtree.

.SS Tag Mirroring
After synchronization, tags pointing at the upstream commit are mirrored
locally using:

.nf
git tag -f TAG SHA
.fi

.SS Commit Message Format
Automatic commits use the format:

.nf
Sync from REMOTE/BRANCH (SHA): SUBJECT
.fi

.SH ENVIRONMENT

.TP
.B GSYNCH_URL
Default URL for the upstream repository.

.TP
.B GSYNCH_BRANCH
Default branch name.

.SH EXIT STATUS

.TP
0
Synchronization completed successfully or no changes were necessary.

.TP
>0
An error occurred or local state prevented synchronization.

.SH SEE ALSO
git(1)

